[1
Date: Sun, 16 Dec 2001 22:07:35 -0500
From: Robert S. Lewis <macaque@bigfoot.com>

Only 2 species of great apes are found in Gabon, the common chimpanzee
(_Pan troglodytes_) and the Western Lowland Gorilla (_Gorilla gorilla
gorilla_). Only the chimpanzees kill and eat duiker [antelope. Mammal
prey includes other primates (including human infants in extremely
rare cases!), bushpigs, rodents, hyraxes, and bushbucks. They eat
several bird species, ants, termites, wasps, and grubs. The eastern
gorilla is mainly frugivorous, eating larger fruit and mature stems,
with the only animal prey being termites, caterpillars, and other
insect larvae.
Gorillas and chimpanzees in this area may be sympatric but they don't
mingle. Feeding areas are sometimes shared but gorilla and chimp
troops take turns feeding. The relationship is one of keeping a
healthy distance from one another if they are sympatric.
As gorillas and chimps differ in their diet with regard to meat, I
believe that the duiker is not our missing link BUT the 2 apes share
much of the same diet. Now which of these types of foods are consumed
by duikers?
Common foods of both species: termites, insect larvae, leaves, fruit,
pith, bark, stems, herbs.
[Some useful references include:
Jenkins PA. Catalogue of Primates in the British Museum (Natural
History) and Elsewhere in the British Isles, Part 5. Natural History
Museum Publications, London.
Remis M. 1995. Gorillas in the trees: the implication of body size and
social context. Paper presented at New York Consortium in Evolutionary
Primatology/New York Regional Primatology Colloquium, City Univ of New
York, New York.
Rodgers ME, Maisels F, Williamson EA, Fernandez M, Tutin CEG. 1990.
Gorilla diet in the Lope Reserve, Gabon: a nutritional analysis.
Oecologia 84:326-339.
Goodall J. 1996. The Chimpanzees of Gombe: Patterns of Behavior.
Belknap Press of Harvard Univ Press, Cambridge.
Boesch C and Boesch H. 1989. Hunting behavior of wild chimpanzees in
the Tai National Park. American Journal of Physical Anthropology,
78:547-73.
--
Robert S. Lewis
