[2
Date: Sun, 16 Dec 2001 13:06:10 -0800
From: Merritt Clifton <anmlpepl@whidbey.com>

Chimps do this; gorillas don't. Also, chimps and gorillas usually
occupy separate habitat and don't fraternize, although they might come
into conflict under circumstances of displacement due to logging or
warfare.
Of possible relevance here might be that either a chimp or gorilla
carcass would be readily scavenged by humans, not just for meat but
also for parts used in various kinds of animist ceremony, and/or sold
for souvenirs.
Finding the evidence, however, would be complicated because chimps and
gorillas, although heavily poached, are both nominally protected
species, and anyone in possession of their remains would have a motive
to lie about what they have and where it came from.
A duiker [antelope would also readily be scavenged. These are
commonly caught with wire snares, and have sometimes been dead for a
couple of days before their remains are collected.
Are people really sure this outbreak is Ebola and not some other type
of hemorragic fever, or a confluence of Ebola in some cases and
something else in another? I'm not aware of any previous outbreaks of
Ebola ever being definitively traced to ungulates. If that occurred,
Ebola would logically be a disease of livestock, and would accordingly
almost certainly be much more common and better known. [Correct. No
virus isolations have been made from these gorillas, chimps, or
antelope. They could have died of 3 -- or more -- different causes. -
Mod.JW
