From: Karen Edge <KEdge@salud.unm.edu>

Just a comment - when I was in Peace Corps in Gabon in the mid-80's,
duiker, which were locally known as gazelle, was one of the most
common meals we ate "au village." It seems that if the gorillas and
chimps had been infected through eating gazelle, there should be more
human cases through the same route, as opposed to being infected by
eating the chimp itself. [That is a good point. However, were you in
what is now known to be an Ebola-affected area of Gabon? The
infection may be localized, like yellow fever. - Mod.JW
