[5
Date: Mon, 17 Dec 2001 10:16:14 +0000
From: Conor Kretsch <Conor.Kretsch@enviros.com>

Regarding apes and Ebola, gorillas do not hunt other mammals and are
strictly vegetarian, therefore duikers [antelope are unlikely to
provide a missing link through the food chain in this way.
However, in parts of Gabon and the Congo (and elsewhere), apes and
duikers (and obviously dozens of other mammal species) are known to
share pools sometimes deep within the forest, for drinking and
bathing -- which may indicate several potential routes for
transmission. If it is determined that apes and duikers have died as a
result of Ebola infection, I would think it important that these
communal gathering places, animals visiting them, and invertebrates in
or near the water are investigated. The ecological significance of
these 'watering holes' can be assumed by the numbers of animals
visiting them. Many of these have been only recently discovered by
western science during forest expeditions. Assuming that these places
or others like them have been frequented by forest animals for
hundreds if not thousands of years, certainly the possibility exists
that such infections and cycles of transmission have been around for
just as long.
Whatever the source, perhaps Ebola in humans (as perhaps with Marburg,
and as suggested for HIV: Gao et al, Nature, Vol. 397, pp. 436-441,
Feb. 4, 1999) is just another knock-on effect of encroachment and the
expansion of the bush meat trade?
--
Conor E. Kretsch
Consultant Scientist
Enviros
Unit 4, The Plaza,
Swords, Co. Dublin
Ireland
